Covid-19 By The Numbers

The Covid-19 pandemic was a devastating and unique event in our history. It created lasting transformations for society and still remains a controversial topic. Opinions range on masks, effectiveness of lock-down mandates, the lethality of the virus, and every facet of the pandemic.
This presentation will examine the data set of number of deaths of individuals infected with Covid-19 at the time of their death. This data set was produced by the U.S Department of Health & Human Services and is available at this link. The data for 2020 and 2021 is final while 2022 and 2023 are provisional.
The presentation will contain another data set to supplement the Covid-19 data set with national and state wide population figures. The presentation will use the 2020 census from the United States Census Bureau for population figures, available at this link.

Questions that the data set should answere include:

  • Which condition contributed to more deaths?
  • How is age related to deaths?
  • Which year had the most deaths?
  • What is the death-rate per month?
  • How many total deaths per State were there?
  • What is the percentage of deaths per State?

The data set consists of 13 columns and over 550 thousand rows. Each row consists of 2 observations “COVID.19.Deaths” and “Number.of.Mentions”. However, “COVID.19.Deaths” is a more well-defined subset of “Number.of.Mentions”, so we will exclude the latter. Each row consists of the number of deaths of a different sub-group, where sub-groups range from Total United States, individual states, multiple age-groups, condition that contributed to the Covid related death, yearly deaths, total deaths to date, and monthly deaths.

National total of deaths per pre-existing medical condition:

As seen here respitory and circulatory dieseases were the leading contributing factors to covid related deaths, with over 1.2 million and 800 thousands. Covid-19 alone killed over 1 million americans with no pre-existing diseases.

Total Deaths by Condition and Age.

If we color the graph above by age we can see that the older a person is contributes to total deaths.

National Total by Age:

As seen here age is a major contributing factor to deaths caused by Covid. This is telling as to why the CDC recomended staying away from elderly family members during the pandemic.

Monthly Totals and timeline of Covid-19 deaths:

As we see here, the end of 2020 leading into the beginning of 2021 was the extreme of the pandemic and why many states chose to enforce lockdowns untill death rates came down.

Yearly Stats:

2021 was the year with the most deaths. Which is no suprise since the previous graph showed the peak month with over 400 thousand deaths being January of 2021.

Timeline of Deaths:

create_total_to_date <- function(data_V) {
  new_V <- vector("integer", length(data_V))
  new_V[1] = data_V[1]
  for(x in 2:length(data_V))
    new_V[x] = new_V[x - 1] + data_V[x]
  return(new_V)
}

Since the data only contained discrete values of deaths per group, the function above creates a continous variable of the total deaths from start to end.

Summary

I chose to work with this data set because I was personally interested in the severity of Covid-19 as well as how the different ways states handled the pandemic compared to one another. The data reveals that the virus is extremely deadly when it comes to age and underlying circulatory and respiratory diseases. Also, we can see that the total number lost versus the percent of population lost tell different stories on how the virus affected individual states. The data shows that if some of the states with larger populations would have chosen to handle the pandemic the same way as some of the smaller population states, then the total number of US deaths could have been much larger.
